subsection.p:
(50)
Den Dikken et al. (2000):
a. ‘Type A’ specificational pseudoclefts
• feature as their major constituents a wh-clause and a full IP (which is subject to optional ellipsis);
• have wh < XP orders only;
• exhibit connectivity effects for negative polarity.
b. ‘Type B’ specificational pseudoclefts
• feature as their major constituents a wh-clause and some XP (X ≠ I);
• have XP < wh orders;
• do not exhibit connectivity effects for negative polarity.

(53)
Specificational pseudoclefts consist of:
• a constituent containing a variable (also called identified (Huddleston 1971));
• a constituent (exhaustively) specifying the value for that variable (also called identifier (Huddleston 1971), focus (Akmajian 1979, Higgins 1979), highlighted constituent (Collins 1991), counterweight (Heycock and Kroch 1999));
• a form of the copula linking the two major constituents.

(184)
a. What we saw in the park was a man and a woman.
b. {x: we saw x in the park} = {a man, a woman}
